# Mid-turn cancel via Ctrl-C, exercised through a tool that polls the
# cancel flag. Mock turn 1 emits a bash tool_call running `sleep 3`;
# while the child sleeps, we send Ctrl-C through the PTY. The bash
# tool's poll loop observes the flag, kills the shell, and returns a
# cancellation error. The agent's outer loop then sees the cancel
# flag at the top of the next iteration and returns cleanly.
#
# A second user prompt re-arms the agent; the mock script's pointer is
# now at turn 2, which streams a recovery sentinel. Asserting on that
# sentinel proves both that the cancel unwound the agent thread
# without wedging it and that the runner can accept fresh input
# afterwards. A regression that left the runner stuck in a tool
# would either time out at `wait_idle` or never surface the sentinel.

spawn ./zig-out/bin/zag
wait_text /Welcome to zag/
wait_idle 500ms
send "run sleep" <Enter>
wait_idle 1s
send <C-c>
wait_idle 2s
send "again" <Enter>
wait_idle 5s
expect_text /recovery-after-cancel/
send "/quit" <Enter>
wait_exit
